.
I built my life and career by refusing to quit. 
 
As a professional athlete, you’re taught the opposite of quitting is winning. If you quit, you’ll never win. If you quit, you are out of the game.
 
All of that is still inside me. I don’t think I’ll ever be completely rid of it—but this conversation opened me up to see quitting a bit differently now.
 
Five and a half years ago, I quit representing my country. I quit being a teammate. I quit a marriage. I quit drinking. I did all of that within a 5-month period.
 
And had I not done all those things, I don’t think I would have met Glennon. I think we would have missed each other.  I attribute so much of my happiness now to moments where my life wasn't working for me, and I had to make choices. And some of those choices involved quitting things that weren't serving me.
 
I loved this conversation about Quitting with Glennon and Amanda on this week’s We Can Do Hard Things podcast. I hope you do, too.
 
Listen at the link in my bio.

I’m on Glennon’s podcast We Can Do Hard Things today talking about the five fights we have over and over (and over) again, how we learned to navigate our *very* different approaches to conflict, and how we realized — in the endless Groundhog Day of quarantine — that each of our separate fights are actually about THE EXACT SAME THING.  Spoiler alert: It’s not actually about the milkshake. (Even though it’s still a little about the milkshake.)
 
I love you @glennondoyle. Even when you leave a full cup of coffee in the washing machine.
 
Listen to our conversation on We Can Do Hard Things at the link in my bio.  And follow the pod so you get all the new episodes (How fun was the episode where I tried to teach G how to have fun??)
Abby

For weeks, I’ve been behind the scenes making sure the mics are on, the headphones are plugged in, and the files are uploaded—but today, I am finally on my wife’s new podcast, We Can Do Hard Things, talking about my favorite subject: FUN.
 
All I’m looking for in life is to have fun. Glennon has no idea what fun is. So I’m having an invention with both Glennon and her sister Amanda about making time for fun, and deciding what they like to do for fun. They have no idea. 
 
My favorite part was listening to my wife talk about how she loves watching our Women’s National Team play and why it makes her so emotional. Listen through the link in my bio.
 
I think we made some progress on the fun front.
 
Hopefully, @glennondoyle will have me back soon 😉

node.text:
**100% of what @together.rising receives in donations through Friday will be deployed to provide urgent relief from yesterday’s devastating earthquake in Haiti. Please join us in standing with the people of Haiti by giving at TogetherRising.org/give (link in my bio).**

Yesterday morning, a massive, 7.2 magnitude earthquake struck Haiti, leaving at least 724 people dead. More than 2,800 people are injured. Hundreds more are missing. Thousands more are in urgent need of medical care, shelter, and vital supplies—even as the country braces for Tropical Storm Grace.

Hospitals and clinics are overwhelmed. Hundreds of homes and buildings have been destroyed, leaving countless families and children without shelter. The need for relief efforts is enormous—and is only expected to grow. 

@together.rising has invested in the people of Haiti since 2015, including funding a maternity wing to allow pregnant people to welcome their babies with dignity, and with an investment just last month of $100,000, which included funding a medically-equipped van that will provide urgent medical services.

We will continue to stand with the people of Haiti throughout the aftermath of yesterday’s excruciating earthquake. 

Today, we are committing $250,000 in urgent relief, including investing in boots-on-the-ground organizations to bring medical response and hospital accessibility to remote areas where it is needed most—and we are also directing 100% of all donations we receive now through Friday to relief efforts in Haiti.

Please consider joining us in standing with the people of Haiti through a donation of any size at TogetherRising.org/give (link in my bio).

I built my life and career by refusing to quit. 
 
As a professional athlete, you’re taught the opposite of quitting is winning. If you quit, you’ll never win. If you quit, you are out of the game.
 
All of that is still inside me. I don’t think I’ll ever be completely rid of it—but this conversation opened me up to see quitting a bit differently now.
 
Five and a half years ago, I quit representing my country. I quit being a teammate. I quit a marriage. I quit drinking. I did all of that within a 5-month period.
 
And had I not done all those things, I don’t think I would have met Glennon. I think we would have missed each other.  I attribute so much of my happiness now to moments where my life wasn't working for me, and I had to make choices. And some of those choices involved quitting things that weren't serving me.
 
I loved this conversation about Quitting with Glennon and Amanda on this week’s We Can Do Hard Things podcast. I hope you do, too.
 
Listen at the link in my bio.

I’m back this week on the We Can Do Hard Things podcast talking to Glennon and Amanda about SEX!!!!! I do get a touch embarrassed, but I think it’s important that we talk about sex more openly. 

In this episode, you will hear: 

➡️ Our sex origin stories 
➡️ The biggest sex challenges in my marriage with G
➡️ Amanda’s regrets of her past
➡️ How the pod squaders taught us about “lesbian bed death.” (We like our phrasing better—lesbian deathbed.) 
➡️ And don’t you worry, we do speak of Glennon and my first time, and how that didn’t go quite as you would have expected it to go. 

Listen at the link in my bio.

What you can see, you can be.

It matters that I get to sit with my daughters and son and cheer as Ashleigh Johnson, Crystal Dunn, Alex Morgan, Oksana Masters, and countless other women athletes translate years of tireless excellence into a chance for glory in Tokyo.

Women athletes were banned from the first Olympics, the first women competitors broke through in the 1900 Games. 2012 was the first time every delegation sent at least one woman to the Olympics. This summer, women will compete in more than 300 Olympic events.

There is progress, and there is still so much work to do. Girls are two times more likely to drop out of sports by age 14.  I’m proud to work with @SecretDeodorant in making youth sports a positive part of girls’ lives.  We need to watch our girls, cheer for them, and say over and over again: “I love watching you play.”

So that our girls will stay in the sports they love, pursue their excellence and—most importantly—in response to anyone who ever questions who and what they can be, they can stand in their power and say: “Just Watch Me.”

#WatchMe
#SecretDeoPartner

I joined Glennon on the We Can Do Hard Things podcast this week to talk about something incredibly personal and hard. I was surprised by how much I ended up sharing, and how healing it was for me. 
 
If you have ever experienced an inner conflict between who you are and a community, institution, family, or identity you love, or if you are still healing from the scars of being taught that who you are is wrong, or you don’t belong, I hope this conversation will be as healing for you as it was for me.
 
I never knew how much I needed to talk through this. So, thank you, Glennon, for inviting me, and thank you for inviting all of us into the messiest, hardest, most important conversations. 
Listen at the link in my bio. 
Abby
